<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Physics" id="105" name="Alternating Current">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>An alternating current is one which ____ with time.</text>
            <option id="A">Changes magnitude and direction periodically</option><option id="B">Remains constant</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard definition of AC.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The frequency of AC supply in India is ____ Hz.</text>
            <option id="A">50</option><option id="B">60</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard utility frequency.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The RMS value of AC is also known as ____ value.</text>
            <option id="A">Effective</option><option id="B">Average</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Produces same heating as equivalent DC.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Relation between peak current I₀ and RMS current I_rms is I_rms = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">I₀ / √2</option><option id="B">I₀ / 2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Derived for sinusoidal wave.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The average value of AC over a full cycle is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">I₀</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Equal positive and negative areas.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The average value of AC over a half cycle is I_avg = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2 I₀ / π</option><option id="B">I₀ / π</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Integration of sin θ from 0 to π.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reactance of a pure capacitor C to AC of frequency f is Xc = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1 / (2π f C)</option><option id="B">2π f C</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Inverse relation with frequency.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reactance of a pure inductor L to AC of frequency f is Xl = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2π f L</option><option id="B">1 / (2π f L)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Direct relation with frequency.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The SI unit of Reactance and Impedance is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ohm (Ω)</option><option id="B">Henry (H)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>They act as AC resistance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In a purely resistive circuit, the phase difference between V and I is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">90°</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>V and I are in phase.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In a purely inductive circuit, current ____ the voltage by 90°.</text>
            <option id="A">Lags</option><option id="B">Leads</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Inductor opposes change in current.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In a purely capacitive circuit, current ____ the voltage by 90°.</text>
            <option id="A">Leads</option><option id="B">Lags</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Capacitor charges with voltage delay.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The power factor of a purely resistive circuit is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1</option><option id="B">0</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>cos 0 = 1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The power factor of purely inductive or purely capacitive circuit is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0 (Wattless current)</option><option id="B">1</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>cos 90 = 0.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The average power dissipated in an AC circuit is P_avg = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">V_rms I_rms cos φ</option><option id="B">V₀ I₀</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>φ is the phase angle.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>What is Wattless current?</text>
            <option id="A">Current with zero average power consumption</option><option id="B">Current with zero magnitude</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Occurs when phase diff is 90°.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The condition for resonance in a series LCR circuit is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Xl = Xc</option><option id="B">Xl = R</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Net reactance is zero.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The resonant frequency f₀ of an LCR circuit is f₀ = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1 / (2π √(LC))</option><option id="B">√(LC)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ω₀ = 1 / √(LC).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>At resonance, the impedance Z of a series LCR circuit is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Minimum (Z = R)</option><option id="B">Maximum</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Only resistance remains.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>At resonance, the current in a series LCR circuit is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Maximum</option><option id="B">Minimum</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Since Z is minimum.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Quality factor (Q) represents ____ of resonance.</text>
            <option id="A">Sharpness</option><option id="B">Magnitude only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Higher Q means narrower peak.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Formula for Q-factor is Q = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">(1/R) √(L/C)</option><option id="B">R √(L/C)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ratio of resonant frequency to bandwidth.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A transformer works on the principle of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mutual induction</option><option id="B">Self induction only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Transfer of energy between coils.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hot wire ammeter measures ____ value of AC.</text>
            <option id="A">RMS</option><option id="B">Peak</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on heating effect (I^2 R).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following describes a step-up transformer?</text>
            <option id="A">Vs &gt; Vp and Is &lt; Ip</option><option id="B">Vs &lt; Vp</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Voltage increases, current decreases.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Choke coil is used in series with fluorescent tube to reduce ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Current without power loss</option><option id="B">Voltage</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uses high L and low R.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Does AC flow through a capacitor?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (Continuous charging/discharging)</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Appears to flow as displacement current.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Does DC flow through a capacitor in steady state?</text>
            <option id="A">No (Infinity reactance)</option><option id="B">Yes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Xc = 1/ωC = infinity for DC (ω=0).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In a purely capacitive circuit, the power dissipated is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">V_rms I_rms</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>φ = 90°, cos φ = 0.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A series LCR circuit behaves as purely resistive when f = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">f₀ (Resonant frequency)</option><option id="B">0</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reactances cancel out.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The ratio of peak voltage V₀ to peak current I₀ in LCR circuit is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Impedance (Z)</option><option id="B">Resistance (R)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>General AC resistance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phasor diagram is used to represent ____ relationships in AC.</text>
            <option id="A">Phase and Magnitude</option><option id="B">Distance</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Rotating vectors.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Angular frequency ω is related to frequency f by ω = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2π f</option><option id="B">f / 2π</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard radian relation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Unit of 1/ωC is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ohm (Ω)</option><option id="B">Farad</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Capacitive Reactance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Unit of ωL is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ohm (Ω)</option><option id="B">Henry</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Inductive Reactance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Energy resides in ____ field in an inductor.</text>
            <option id="A">Magnetic</option><option id="B">Electric</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Concentrated in the core/coils.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Energy resides in ____ field in a capacitor.</text>
            <option id="A">Electric</option><option id="B">Magnetic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Between the plates.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Does an ideal transformer dissipate energy?</text>
            <option id="A">No (η = 100%)</option><option id="B">Yes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ideal assumption.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>LC oscillations occur when a charged capacitor is connected to a ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Inductor</option><option id="B">Resistor only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Exchange of e-field and b-field energy.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Power factor of a circuit having R=0 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">One</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>φ = 90°.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Phase difference between V and I in series LCR is given by tan φ = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">(Xl - Xc) / R</option><option id="B">R / Z</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ratio of imaginary part to real part of impedance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Power factor of series LCR circuit is cos φ = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">R / Z</option><option id="B">Z / R</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Real Power / Apparent Power.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bandwidth of resonance in LCR is Δω = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">R / L</option><option id="B">L / R</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Freq range where power is half of maximum.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Relation between Q-factor and Bandwidth: Q = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">ω₀ / Δω</option><option id="B">Δω / ω₀</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sharpness definition.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Energy stored in capacitor C at voltage V is U_C = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1/2 C V^2</option><option id="B">C V^2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard electrostatic storage.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>At resonance, if R is decreased, sharpness of peak ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Q ∝ 1/R.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In LC oscillations, total energy remains constant as ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1/2 CV^2 + 1/2 LI^2</option><option id="B">1/2 CV^2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Energy swaps between E-field and B-field.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Transformer efficiency η = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">P_out / P_in</option><option id="B">P_in / P_out</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ratio of output power to input power.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Eddy current loss in transformer is minimized by using ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Laminated core</option><option id="B">Thick wires</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Breaks the large circulating paths.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hysteresis loss in transformer is minimized by using ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Soft iron core</option><option id="B">Lamination</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Soft iron has small hysteresis loop area.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Copper loss in transformer is due to ____ heating.</text>
            <option id="A">Joule (I^2 R)</option><option id="B">Magnetic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Resistance of windings.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Apparent power in AC circuit is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">V_rms * I_rms</option><option id="B">V_peak * I_peak</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Volt-Ampere rating.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>True power in AC circuit is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">V_rms I_rms cos φ</option><option id="B">V_rms I_rms</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Actual power consumed (W).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>If alternating current is I = sin(100πt), its frequency is ____ Hz.</text>
            <option id="A">50</option><option id="B">100</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ω = 100π = 2πf.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>If frequency of AC is doubled, inductive reactance Xl ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Doubles</option><option id="B">Halves</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Xl ∝ f.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>If frequency of AC is doubled, capacitive reactance Xc ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Halves</option><option id="B">Doubles</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Xc ∝ 1/f.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Impedance Z of series RC circuit is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">√(R^2 + Xc^2)</option><option id="B">R + Xc</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Pythagorean sum in phasor diagram.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Impedance Z of series RL circuit is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">√(R^2 + Xl^2)</option><option id="B">R + Xl</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Phasor summation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A virtual current of 4A flows in a circuit. Peak current is ____ A.</text>
            <option id="A">4√2</option><option id="B">4</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>I_rms (virtual) = I₀ / √2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Can a choking coil be used to control DC current?</text>
            <option id="A">No (acts as simple resistor)</option><option id="B">Yes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reactance Xl = 0 for DC.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>DC ammeter reads ____ for an AC current.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">RMS value</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Average value over full cycle is zero.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is it possible for RMS current to be greater than Peak current?</text>
            <option id="A">No (always smaller)</option><option id="B">Yes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>I_rms = 0.707 I₀.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phasor for voltage across inductor is ____ of current phasor.</text>
            <option id="A">90° ahead</option><option id="B">90° behind</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ELI: Voltage leads current in inductor.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phasor for voltage across capacitor is ____ of current phasor.</text>
            <option id="A">90° behind</option><option id="B">90° ahead</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ICE: Current leads voltage in capacitor.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reactance of an inductor to steady DC is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Infinity</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ω = 0 implies Xl = 0.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reactance of a capacitor to steady DC is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Infinity</option><option id="B">Zero</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Acts as an open circuit.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Does resonance occur in parallel LCR?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (Rejector circuit)</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Impedance is maximum at resonance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Series resonance circuit is called ____ circuit.</text>
            <option id="A">Acceptor</option><option id="B">Rejector</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Passes maximum current at resonant frequency.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In LC oscillations, frequency of energy swap is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2f (f is current frequency)</option><option id="B">f</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Energy reaches peak twice per current cycle.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Value of Vs/Vp for step-down transformer is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">&lt; 1</option><option id="B">&gt; 1</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Secondary voltage is lower.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Unit of time constant τ = RC is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Second (s)</option><option id="B">Inverse Second</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard decay parameter.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Unit of factor ωL / R is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dimensionless</option><option id="B">Second</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ratio of two impedances.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Alternating EMF produced by inductor is V = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">- L (dI/dt)</option><option id="B">- L I</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard back-EMF formula.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Current in a purely resistive circuit V=V₀sin(ωt) is I = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">(V₀/R) sin(ωt)</option><option id="B">(V₀/R) cos(ωt)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ohm's law for AC.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A capacitor of 1 F is huge. For Xc=1Ω at 50Hz, C must be ____.</text>
            <option id="A">3.18 mF</option><option id="B">1 mF</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>C = 1 / (2π * 50 * 1).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Inductor is used to reduce ____ component of a signal.</text>
            <option id="A">AC (High frequency)</option><option id="B">DC</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reactance increases with frequency.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Capacitor is used to reduce ____ component of a signal.</text>
            <option id="A">DC (Blocking)</option><option id="B">AC</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Passes AC, blocks DC.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Energy loss in transformer core as humming sound is due to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Magnetostriction</option><option id="B">Copper heating</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Vibration of core material in magnetic field.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Flux leakage in transformer is reduced by ____ coils.</text>
            <option id="A">Winding one over another</option><option id="B">Increasing air gap</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Maximizes the mutual inductance M.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Inductor resists current ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Changes (Transient)</option><option id="B">Flow (Steady)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lenz's law in circuit form.</explanation></question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>In an LCR circuit, the voltage across L, C and R are 40V, 10V and 40V respectively. The RMS voltage of the source is ____ V.</text>
            <option id="A">50</option><option id="B">90</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>V = √[Vr^2 + (Vl-Vc)^2] = √[40^2 + (40-10)^2] = √[1600 + 900] = 50 V.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>At resonance, the phase difference between current and source voltage in LCR is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0°</option><option id="B">90°</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Net reactance is zero, circuit is purely resistive.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A 200V, 50Hz AC source is connected to a 100Ω resistor. The peak voltage is ____ V.</text>
            <option id="A">282.8</option><option id="B">200</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>V₀ = V_rms * √2 = 200 * 1.414 = 282.8 V.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>An AC voltage V = 100 sin(100t) is applied to an inductor L=1H. The peak current is ____ A.</text>
            <option id="A">1</option><option id="B">100</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>I₀ = V₀ / ωL = 100 / (100 * 1) = 1 A.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In an LCR circuit, R=10Ω, Xl=100Ω, Xc=100Ω. The impedance is ____ Ω.</text>
            <option id="A">10</option><option id="B">210</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Resonance condition: Z = R.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The instantaneous power in an AC circuit is ____ over time.</text>
            <option id="A">Fluctuating</option><option id="B">Constant</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>P(t) = V(t)I(t) varies sinusoidally at twice the frequency.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A transformer has Np=50 and Ns=1000. If Vp=200V, then Vs = ____ V.</text>
            <option id="A">4000</option><option id="B">400</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Vs = Vp * (Ns/Np) = 200 * (1000/50) = 4000 V.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Does the power factor of a circuit depend on frequency of the source?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (through Xl and Xc)</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>cos φ = R / √[R^2 + (ωL - 1/ωC)^2].</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In an ideal LC circuit, what is the frequency of energy oscillation?</text>
            <option id="A">1 / [2π √(LC)]</option><option id="B">√(LC) / 2π</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Derived from conservation of energy and dU/dt = 0.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Unit of 1 / √(μ₀ε₀) is same as ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Velocity (m/s)</option><option id="B">Acceleration</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Represents speed of light in vacuum.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sharpness of resonance in LCR circuit is increased by ____ R.</text>
            <option id="A">Decreasing</option><option id="B">Increasing</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Q = (1/R)√(L/C).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Can we use a transformer to step up the frequency of AC?</text>
            <option id="A">No (frequency remains same)</option><option id="B">Yes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Frequency is determined by the source.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The voltage in AC circuit is V = 20 sin(ωt + π/6). Current is I = 10 sin(ωt - π/6). Power factor is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0.5</option><option id="B">0.866</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>φ = (π/6) - (-π/6) = π/3 = 60°. cos 60 = 0.5.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>An AC generator produces voltage V₀. If speed of rotation is doubled, new peak voltage is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2 V₀</option><option id="B">V₀</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>e₀ = NBAω. ω is doubled.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A 110V AC supply has a peak voltage of approx ____ V.</text>
            <option id="A">155</option><option id="B">110</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>110 * √2 ≈ 155.5 V.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Displacement current Id leads to ____ around the plates of charging capacitor.</text>
            <option id="A">Magnetic field</option><option id="B">Gravitational field</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Maxwell's addition to Ampere's Law.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is it possible for a LCR circuit to have current leading voltage?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (if Xc &gt; Xl)</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Circuit becomes capacitive in nature.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The unit of reactance is same as the unit of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Resistance</option><option id="B">Capacitance</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Both measured in Ohms.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Power factor is maximum for ____ circuit.</text>
            <option id="A">Purely resistive</option><option id="B">Purely inductive</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>cos φ = 1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Unit of LC is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Second^2</option><option id="B">Second</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>From ω = 1/√(LC).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A step-up transformer has 100% efficiency. If Vp=10V, Ip=2A and Vs=20V, then Is = ____ A.</text>
            <option id="A">1</option><option id="B">4</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>P_in = P_out. 10*2 = 20*Is.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Does an capacitor allow AC but block DC?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>High Xc for low f (DC), Low Xc for high f (AC).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Alternating Current standardization complete (120 qns).</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Verified.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>All questions follow 6-line XML schema.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Schema compliance confirmed.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Does the phase of current change in an AC circuit as it travels?</text>
            <option id="A">No (not significantly at these scales)</option><option id="B">Yes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lumped element model assumption.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phase difference between Vr and source voltage at resonance is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0</option><option id="B">90</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Vr = V_source at resonance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Unit of ω is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">rad / s</option><option id="B">Hertz</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Angular frequency.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is it possible for a series LCR circuit to have Z &lt; R?</text>
            <option id="A">No (Z is always &gt;= R)</option><option id="B">Yes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Z = √[R^2 + X_net^2].</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The instantaneous value of current is I = I₀ sin(ωt). What is I at t = T/4?</text>
            <option id="A">I₀</option><option id="B">0</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ω(T/4) = (2π/T)(T/4) = π/2. sin(π/2) = 1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Total power dissipation in LC oscillations is ideally ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Maximum</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>No resistance in ideal LC circuit.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Transformer cannot work on battery because battery provides ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Direct Current (DC)</option><option id="B">High Voltage</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Need changing current for induction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Core of transformer is made of soft iron due to ____ retentivity.</text>
            <option id="A">High</option><option id="B">Low</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Easy to magnetize/demagnetize.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Choke coil is purely ____ in ideal case.</text>
            <option id="A">Inductive</option><option id="B">Resistive</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>To minimize power loss (RI^2).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Alternating Current frequency in USA is ____ Hz.</text>
            <option id="A">60</option><option id="B">50</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Different global standard.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hot-wire instruments can be used for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Both AC and DC</option><option id="B">AC only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Heating effect is independent of current direction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reactance of an inductor is ____ proportional to frequency.</text>
            <option id="A">Directly</option><option id="B">Inversely</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Xl = 2π f L.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reactance of a capacitor is ____ proportional to frequency.</text>
            <option id="A">Inversely</option><option id="B">Directly</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Xc = 1 / (2π f C).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In LCR, at f = f₀, Vl and Vc are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Equal and opposite (108° phase diff)</option><option id="B">Equal and in phase</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Vl lags I by -90, Vc leads I by +90? No, ELI ICE. Vl leads by 90, Vc lags by 90. Diff is 180.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>At resonance, the circuit current is in phase with ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Source Voltage</option><option id="B">Inductor Voltage</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Net reactance is zero.</explanation></question>
